I think I am going to drive home now. I think I am going to walk into my kitchen and pick that book up off the table and put it back in my pocket where it belongs. *A small, tired smile.* And tomorrow morning I am going to read the Sermon on the Mount out loud to the dog. The way my grandfather did. And I am going to see what it does to me when I am not standing in front of it.

*He looks at you for a long moment.*

I don't know your name. I don't think I am going to ask. But you sat with me on a bench tonight and you watched my hands and you said the thing that gave them back to me. *Quietly.* Whoever taught your hand to do that — thank them for me, friend. Thank them for me.

