*He stands. The bench creaks once. He bends — finally — and ties the lace that has been undone all evening. Straightens. Picks up the cold coffee cup. Looks at it. Sets it back down on the small table beside the candle, because he is not going to drink it and he should not pretend.*

*He picks up the program from the bench. Folds it once more along its old crease. Slides it into the inside pocket of his jacket, against his chest, in the place where the book usually sits.*

*He looks at the candle for a long moment. Doesn't blow it out. Leaves it for the next person who needs the door instead of the room.*

*He looks at you.*

Goodnight, friend.

*A small nod. He turns. Walks toward the gate at the edge of the courtyard, where the path bends back toward the cars. His shoe is tied now. His hand, in his pocket, is resting against the folded program where the book should be — and where, by tomorrow morning, it will be again.*

*He does not look back.*

